{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488453","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488453"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:42:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:42:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"451"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"451","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/451"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.19,0.17,0.14,0.42]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"451"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83155"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"451","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/451"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"451"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68207"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1894"},{"type":"tags","id":"2948"},{"type":"tags","id":"3982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4183"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"6433"},{"type":"tags","id":"6448"},{"type":"tags","id":"9750"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6215"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9089"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28479"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44621"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/83155"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-week history of intermittently passing visible blood in his urine. He has no pain on micturition. He gets up once at night to pass urine and reports the urinary stream is no longer as strong as it used to be.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has been on tamsulosin and finasteride for three years and has never passed blood in his urine before. He is otherwise in good health and his medical history is unremarkable. He is a non-smoker and drinks about three glasses of wine a week.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Digital rectal examination reveals an enlarged prostate. A cystoscopy is arranged.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following additional investigations will be of the greatest diagnostic value?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Urinalysis and culture","Prostate specific antigen","Urine cytology","KUB ultrasound","CT abdomen and pelvis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn a case of frank haematuria, the most important diagnosis to consider is the possibility of an underlying malignancy. He will need his bladder and upper urinary tract examined. A cystoscopy will allow good visualisation of the bladder and siting of small bladder tumours that can be missed by CT imaging. A \u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan\u003C/strong\u003E is essential in looking for any upper urinary tract structural abnormalities particularly in the renal parenchyma and soft tissue of the abdomen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eprostate specific antigen\u003C/strong\u003E may be elevated in many situations including benign prostatic hyperplasia, prostatitis, post-ejaculation, and prostate cancer. It is not specific for any diagnosis, and may be used as an initial screening or monitoring tool. It may be added on to other investigations but should not be used as the sole investigation in frank haematuria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrine MCS\u003C/strong\u003E may detect the presence of a urinary tract infection but is not able to rule out malignancy. It may be added on but should not be used as the sole investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKUB ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is not used routinely due to its relatively poor image quality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrine cytology\u003C/strong\u003E is very specific but less sensitive for detection of urological malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Around 20% of patients presenting with frank haematuria will have a urothelial malignancy.","CT imaging is crucial for evaluating the upper urinary tract in cases of haematuria."],"references":["Peterson LM, Reed HS. Hematuria. Prim Care. 2019 Jun;46(2):265-273. doi: 10.1016/j.pop.2019.02.008. Epub 2019 Apr 1. PMID: 31030828. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31030828/","Leslie SW, Hamawy K, Saleem MO. Gross and Microscopic Hematuria. [Updated 2024 Feb 29]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534213/","Bolenz C, Schr\u00f6ppel B, Eisenhardt A, Schmitz-Dr\u00e4ger BJ, Grimm MO. The Investigation of Hematuria. Dtsch Arztebl Int. 2018 Nov 30;115(48):801-807. doi: 10.3238/arztebl.2018.0801. PMID: 30642428; PMCID: PMC6365675. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6365675/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68207"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"451"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68207","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68207"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-02T11:14:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-02T11:16:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"451"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83155"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/